The Federal Capital Territory Administration (FCTA) said that it has put in place necessary measures to ensure food security in the Federal Capital Territory (FCT), in spite of the COVID-19 pandemic. In an interview with LEADERSHIP in Abuja yesterday, acting secretary for Agriculture and Rural Development Secretariat (ARDS), Mr. Ibe Prospect Chukwuemeka explained that the administration had ensured that there is unhindered movement for all those involved in production and sales of agro-products. Chukwuemeka noted that such action has reduced the losses that could have been incurred by the farmers and also enabled them access farm inputs they need for the farming season. The acting secretary, who spoke through the director for planning, research and statistics, Mr. Yahaya Husseni, disclosed that the secretariat has also intensified its extension services to farmers, especially in the rural communities. He revealed that the minister of state for the FCT, Dr Ramatu Tijjani Aliyu, is currently spearheading discussions on the implementation of two agricultural development programmes in the territory. “The first is with the CBN on the implementation of the Accelerated Agricultural Development Scheme (AADS) to support FCT youths in agriculture. Second is with the African Development bank (AfDB) to implement the Agro Industrial Processing Zones with focus to set in motion National Livestock Transformation plan for the FCT. The programmes will transform the agricultural landscape in the FCT, while helping to create employment for FCT populace.”